@Node Introduction "RevFlex V1.0: Introduction"
@{B}______________________________________________________________________________@{UB}
 @{B}@{FG HIGHLIGHT}@{BG SHADOW} I N T R O D U C T I O N @{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT}@{UB}@{BG Shadow}   @{BG Background} @{BG Shadow}  @{BG Background} @{BG Shadow} @{BG Background} @{B}|@{UB} |  |
@{B}@{FG Highlight}¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯@{UB}@{FG Text}
  RevFlex is a reimplementation of FlexRev (c) by Daniel Kahlin.

  It operates just like FlexRev but has a couple of new built-in keywords that
it can process.  Additionally it can bump a build number too.

  Same as FlexRev, RevFlex is designed to be flexible.  It should be possible
to be used with almost any programming language.

@EndNode
@Node Why_clone_FlexRev_(you_fool)? "RevFlex V1.0: Why clone FlexRev (you fool)?"
@{B}______________________________________________________________________________@{UB}
 @{B}@{FG HIGHLIGHT}@{BG SHADOW} W H Y   C L O N E   F L E X R E V   ( Y O U   F O O L ) ? @{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT}@{UB}@{BG Shadow}   @{BG Background} @{BG Shadow}  @{BG Background} @{BG Shadow} @{BG Background} @{B}|@{UB} |  |
@{B}@{FG Highlight}¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯@{UB}@{FG Text}
  RevFlex was mainly written because after more than 20 years of happily using
FlexRev I one day noticed that my usual version.revision sheme didn't really
reflect the way I actually generate the version and revision and has not much
to do with the version number I use when releasing software.

  Whenever I compile a source code and my script notices changes to the to be
compiled source code by querying CED, the revision is updated automatically
via FlexRev.  So when I started thinking about this it quickly became clear
that what I actually needed was a build number which unfortunately FlexRev
does not provide.

  So I searched Aminet for an updated version but only found V0.55.  Funnily
enough the version on my harddisk is v0.73 and I don't know where it came
from.  Unfortunately there was no source code to FlexRev available.

  I then decided to see if I could create a FlexRev replacement that supports
build numbers aswell and started writing down what was needed to create a
FlexRev clone.  On that same afternoon RevFlex was born.  Later that day
around midnight it was almost finished and just needed some intense testing.

  Now that I am writing these lines I'm wondering if I actually should release
RevFlex since probably nobody uses FlexRev nowadays anyway and would not want
to switch over to it or RevFlex as I myself wouldn't want to switch over to
one of the million c-centric or asm-centric or otherweise useless, lacking and
unflexible or just bugged revision bumpers available on Aminet either - you
see, I've tried some others before finally came to the conclusion to recode
FlexRev :-)

  But since you are reading this I probably decided to release it after all :-)



