@Node The_Revfile "RevFlex V1.0: The Revfile"
@{B}______________________________________________________________________________@{UB}
 @{B}@{FG HIGHLIGHT}@{BG SHADOW} T H E   R E V F I L E @{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT}@{UB}@{BG Shadow}   @{BG Background} @{BG Shadow}  @{BG Background} @{BG Shadow} @{BG Background} @{B}|@{UB} |  |
@{B}@{FG Highlight}¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯@{UB}@{FG Text}
  Unlike FlexRev, RevFlex does not need any keywords to be present initially
in the @{B}revfile@{UB}.  If you give it a prototype filename and target it will
initialise @{B}VERSION@{UB}, @{B}REVISION@{UB} and @{B}BUILD@{UB} numbers to zero.

  You can either specify a @{B}PROTO@{UB} and/or @{B}TARGET@{UB} file by providing it via the
CLI or by placing @{B}PROTO@{UB} and @{B}TARGET@{UB} keywords in the revision file itself.

  A @{B}revfile@{UB} is build up by a couple of lines each specifying a keyword
followed by an equal sign '=' and a number or a string.

  RevFlex knows the following keywords:

  @{B}VERSION@{UB}=number  - This is the version number that will get bumped
  @{B}REVISION@{UB}=number - Thiss is the revision number that will get bumped
  @{B}BUILD@{UB}=number    - This is the buildnumber that will get bumped

  RevFlex will parse these keywords and process them in case you want any of
them bumped.

  Additionally you can specify any number of your own keywords aswell and
assign any kind of data to it.  For example if your @{B}prototype file@{UB} always also
builds up a $VER string from the version/revision/build data provided by
RevFlex you can simply set a program name in the @{B}revfile@{UB} that is later
inserted in your target file when generated through the @{B}protofile@{UB}.  So you
can have just a generic @{B}prototype file@{UB} and have specific data like the
program name provided individually per @{B}revfile@{UB}.

Sounds complicated?  Yes, but it is really simple :-)

@{B}@{U}@{FG SHINE}Example REVFILE:@{FG TEXT}@{UU}@{UB}
VERSION=1
REVISION=3
BUILD=1002
NAME=TestProg
AUTHOR=UGelb

Will replace any occurence of @{B}${NAME}@{UB} in your protofile by the string 'TestProg'

In your @{B}protofile@{UB} it could be used like this:
@{B}#define VERSIONSTRING '$VER: ${NAME} ${FULLVER} (${DATE}) © by ${AUTHOR}'@{UB}

  @{B}NAME@{UB} and @{B}AUTHOR@{UB} are untouched by RevFlex, it actually does not know anything
about them and they could just be named @{B}BEER@{UB} and @{B}SPAGHETTI@{UB} for all it cares.
It will just take the values set to them in the @{B}revfile@{UB} and inserts them in
the target file for any occurence of the keyword.

  FULLVER and DATE are actual keywords RevFlex understands and it will
replace them by strings it built up dynamically.


@EndNode
@Node The_Protofile "RevFlex V1.0: The Protofile"
@{B}______________________________________________________________________________@{UB}
 @{B}@{FG HIGHLIGHT}@{BG SHADOW} T H E   P R O T O F I L E @{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT}@{UB}@{BG Shadow}   @{BG Background} @{BG Shadow}  @{BG Background} @{BG Shadow} @{BG Background} @{B}|@{UB} |  |
@{B}@{FG Highlight}¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯@{UB}@{FG Text}
  The @{B}protofile@{UB} is the actual template RevFlex uses to build up the @{B}target@{UB}
source file from.  This can be adapted to your own likings and is very
flexible. In theory it should actually work with any programming language
you can think of.

  RevFlex loads the @{B}protofile@{UB} after it has gathered all needed information from
the @{B}revfile@{UB} and then scans the @{B}protofile@{UB} for @{B}${keyword}@{UB} and parses it.  Each
keyword is then replaced with the data belonging to that keyword.

Keywords defined by RevFlex are:

  VERSION     - replaced by the version number
  VER         - alternative/short for VERSION
  REVISION    - replaced by the revision number
  REV         - alternative/short for REVISION
  BUILD       - replaced by the build number
  VERREV      - replaced by a string made up of: version.revision
  FULLVER     - replaced by a string made up of: version.revision.build
  VERREVBUILD - same as FULLVER, just for completeness
  DATE        - replaced by current date in the format: dd.mm.yyyy
  TIME        - replaced by current time in the format: hh:mm:ss
  DAY         - day of the month without leading zeros
  MONTH       - month without leading zeros
  YEAR        - 4-digit year

  Please note that internal keywords are all uppercase.  Keywords you define
yourself in the @{B}revfile@{UB} can have any case but they must be spelled exactly
the same way then in the @{B}protofile@{UB} to be resolved to their data.

  You can also use the form @{B}${<n>keyword}@{UB} where @{B}<n>@{UB} is a number.  This
will produce exactly @{B}<n>@{UB} chars in the output.  If @{B}keyword@{UB} contains less than
@{B}<n>@{UB} chars it will be padded by spaces and if @{B}keyword@{UB} contains more than @{B}<n>@{UB}
chars it will be truncated.  This also implies that @{B}keywords cannot start
with a digit@{UB}.

  Here is a new feature of RevFlex when compared to FlexRev:  By default the
keyword will be left aligned, e.g.  padding will be added to the right side of
the keyword, using positive numbers, just like FlexRev.  With RevFlex though
it is also possible to have the keyword right aligned with padding added to
the left side of the keyword by passing a negative number.

  Example usage in @{B}protofile@{UB}:
@{B}#define PROGNAME_PADDED_LEFTALIGN "${10NAME}"@{UB}
@{B}#define PROGNAME_PADDED_RIGHTALIGN "${-10NAME}"@{UB}

  If you defined @{B}NAME@{UB} in the @{B}revfile@{UB} as f.ex.  RevFlex, the above two lines
will produce the following output in the @{B}target@{UB} file:
@{B}#define PROGNAME_PADDED_LEFTALIGN "RevFlex   "@{UB}
@{B}#define PROGNAME_PADDED_RIGHTALIGN "   RevFlex"@{UB}



@EndNode
@Node The_Target "RevFlex V1.0: The Target"
@{B}______________________________________________________________________________@{UB}
 @{B}@{FG HIGHLIGHT}@{BG SHADOW} T H E   T A R G E T @{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT}@{UB}@{BG Shadow}   @{BG Background} @{BG Shadow}  @{BG Background} @{BG Shadow} @{BG Background} @{B}|@{UB} |  |
@{B}@{FG Highlight}¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯¯@{UB}@{FG Text}
  The @{B}target@{UB} filename must be given to RevFlex as either an CLI argument or
by specifying it in the @{B}revfile@{UB} itself.

  It is needed in order for RevFlex to store the output generated by parsing
the @{B}protofile@{UB} to and for your compiler to pick it up at compile time of
course.

  It will contain everything specified in the @{B}protofile@{UB} with
keywords/defines replaced by the data belonging to that keyword/define.

@{B}Example @{I}revfile@{UI} that should reside in your programs main directory:@{UB}
PROTO=Work:Sources/amigazeux_revproto.e
TARGET=RevFlex_rev.e
VERSION=1
REVISION=0
BUILD=42
NAME=RevFlex
AUTHOR=Matthias Böcker

@{B}Example @{I}protofile@{UI}, see Work:Sources/amigazeux_revproto.e used by above
example stored somewhere on your harddisk.@{UB}
#define COMPILE_VERSION ${VERSION}
#define COMPILE_REVISION ${REVISION}
#define COMPILE_BUILD ${BUILD}
#define COMPILE_DATE '${DATE}'
#define COMPILE_TIME '${TIME}'
#define PROGRAM_YEAR '${YEAR}'
#define PROGRAM_NAME '${NAME}'
#define PROGRAM_VER '${VERSION}.${REVISION}.${BUILD}' /* same as FULLVER */
#define VERSIONSTRING '$VER: ${NAME} ${FULLVER} (${DATE}) © by ${AUTHOR}'

@{B}Together these two files will produce this output to @{I}target@{UI} RevFlex_rev.e:@{UB}
#define COMPILE_VERSION 1
#define COMPILE_REVISION 0
#define COMPILE_BUILD 42
#define COMPILE_DATE '22.05.2022'
#define COMPILE_TIME '14:25:19'
#define PROGRAM_YEAR '2022'
#define PROGRAM_NAME 'RevFlex'
#define PROGRAM_VER '1.0.42'
#define VERSIONSTRING '$VER: RevFlex 1.0.42 (22.05.2022) © by Matthias Böcker'

RevFlex_rev.e can then be compiled by your favourite compiler (in this case
ECX) and included in your programs source code.


